The one rule I will follow forever
The English → Algorithm → Code bridge
Before writing a single line of code, I write English first. Then I break it into steps. The I write code. Every. Single. Time. This is the rule that fixes my biggest problem — the gap between what I understand and what I can write.
STEP 1
Say it in English like you're explaining to your friend
→
STEP 2
Write numbered steps like instructions
→
STEP 3
Now convert those steps into Java code
Concept 1 — the skeleton (every java program needs this)
How I understand it
Think of a Java program like my college building. The building itself is the class. Inside the building there's one main entrance — that's the main method. Whenever Java runs my code, it always enters from that main entrance. Everything I want to happen, I write inside that entrance.
Real life version: I tell my younger sister "go to the kitchen, take a glass, pour water, bring it to me." Those are my instructions. In Java, I'm telling the computer the same thing — step by step instructions — inside main().
public class MyFirstProgram {          // This is the building (class)

    public static void main(String[] args) {  // This is the entrance (main)

        // I write my instructions here

    }
}
Common mistake beginners make
They forget to close curly braces }. Every opening brace { must have a closing brace }. Think of them like opening and closing a zip bag.
Concept 2 — printing (sir's challenge: print without printf)
How I understand it
My sir said "print Hello World without printf." Here's what he meant — printf is a C language thing. In Java we don't have printf (well, we do but we don't use it as default). In Java, printing means using System.out.println(). That's the Java way of saying "show this on screen."
System.out.println = "Hey system! Use the output! Print this line!"
That's literally what those words mean broken down. System = the computer. out = output. println = print a line.
System.out.println("Hello World");   // prints and goes to next line
System.out.print("Hello");         // prints but stays on same line
System.out.println(42);              // can also print numbers
