Concept 3 — variables (boxes with labels)
How I understand it
You know how in our house we have dabba for rice, dabba for dal, dabba for sugar? Each dabba has a label. A variable is exactly that. A labelled box inside the computer's memory. I tell Java: "create a box, call it 'age', put the number 20 inside it." Done.
int age = 20;
int = what kind of box (for whole numbers)
age = the label on the box
20 = what's inside the box
; = I'm done with this instruction (full stop in English)
int
Box for whole numbers only. Ex: 5, 20, -3, 100
double
Box for decimal numbers. Ex: 87.5, 3.14, 9.8
String
Box for text (always in quotes). Ex: "Sanjana", "Hello"
boolean
Box that holds only true or false. Nothing else.
// Creating boxes (declaring variables)
int age = 20;
double marks = 87.5;
String name = "Sanjana";
boolean isPass = true;

// Showing what's inside the box
System.out.println("My name is: " + name);   // + joins text and variable
System.out.println("My age is: " + age);
System.out.println("My marks: " + marks);
Mistake I must not make
Writing String with small 's' like string. Java is case-sensitive. String starts with capital S always. int, double, boolean are all small letters. Only String is capital.
The correct way
String name = "Sanjana"; ← capital S always
int age = 20; ← small i always
Concept 4 — basic math (java as a calculator)
How I understand it
Java can do math. Just like a calculator. I store numbers in boxes, then do operations on them. The result goes into a new box. Simple.
int a = 10;
int b = 5;

int sum = a + b;        // 15
int diff = a - b;       // 5
int product = a * b;    // 50
int quotient = a / b;   // 2
int remainder = a % b;  // 0 (nothing left after dividing)

System.out.println("Sum = " + sum);
System.out.println("Remainder = " + remainder);
% (modulo) is very important in coding. It tells me what's left after division.
10 % 3 = 1 (because 10 ÷ 3 = 3, and 1 is left over)
I'll use this later to check if a number is even or odd (any number % 2 == 0 means even).
Concept 5 — taking input from user
How I understand it
Till now I was hardcoding values like int age = 20. But what if I want the user to type their own age? I need Scanner. Think of Scanner as ears — it listens to what the user types.
import java.util.Scanner;  // bring Scanner tool into my program

public class TakeInput {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);  // create the ears

        System.out.print("Enter your name: ");
        String name = sc.nextLine();       // listen for text

        System.out.print("Enter your age: ");
        int age = sc.nextInt();            // listen for a number

        System.out.println("Hello " + name + "! You are " + age + " years old.");
    }
}
sc.nextLine()
Read a full line of text (words, sentences)
sc.nextInt()
Read a whole number from user
sc.nextDouble()
Read a decimal number from user
import
Bring an outside tool into my program
